      <hedline>
        <hl1>Another Who Overcame</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Iris Chekenian letter about June 10 article on pianist Leon Fleisher says pianist Byron Janis should have been included in discussion of artists disabled by ailments (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Pianist for Whom Never Was Never an Option'' [June 10]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Pianist for Whom Never Was Never an Option'' [June 10]:</p>
        <p>Holly Brubach's article was fascinating and informative, but in naming great artists disabled by an ailment, she omitted the pianist Byron Janis, who had arthritis and resumed his career nearly a decade ago. Mr. Janis was the most exciting pianist of the 50s and 60s, and his performances of the bone-breaking Rachmaninoff Nos. 2 and 3 piano concertos are still arguably the best in existence.</p>
        <p>Iris Chekenian  New York, N.Y.</p>
        <p>LEON FLEISHER</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
